[SPEAKER_00]: I'd love to have moved to Bedford.

217
00:31:24,795 --> 00:31:26,156
[SPEAKER_00]: But good evening.

218
00:31:26,396 --> 00:31:28,076
[SPEAKER_00]: My name is Rama Varnasi.

219
00:31:28,236 --> 00:31:32,398
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm the political coordinator for local 32BJ at CIU.

220
00:31:33,038 --> 00:31:41,961
[SPEAKER_00]: We represent janitors, security guards, airport workers, 185,000 workers up and down the eastern seaboard, and nearly 20,000 here in this state.

221
00:31:42,681 --> 00:31:51,925
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm here tonight to talk to you about the city contracted janitors and other building service workers who clean Medford School buildings and care for other municipal facilities.

222
00:31:52,605 --> 00:32:01,592
[SPEAKER_00]: These workers provide vital services to city residents, but don't enjoy the same wage standards and job protections that municipal employees have.

223
00:32:02,733 --> 00:32:06,596
[SPEAKER_00]: We recently saw how the lack of protections can harm this workforce and the city.

224
00:32:07,296 --> 00:32:17,965
[SPEAKER_00]: Last summer, Medford Public Schools changed janitorial contractors from Compass Facility Services, that's a union contractor, to Partners Facility Solutions, which is a non-union contractor.

225
00:32:18,926 --> 00:32:24,977
[SPEAKER_00]: The compass employees had a collective bargain agreement that guaranteed annual wage increases, good benefits and job protections.

226
00:32:25,478 --> 00:32:27,402
[SPEAKER_00]: When that non-union contractor took over,

227
00:32:27,955 --> 00:32:32,399
[SPEAKER_00]: It failed to hire, at the time, any of the 14 Compass janitors.

228
00:32:32,659 --> 00:32:41,987
[SPEAKER_00]: Though it's worth flagging that, and I think some of my peers, my colleagues can speak to this, that as of today, just today, many of those 14 got a call for a job offer.

229
00:32:42,468 --> 00:32:45,831
[SPEAKER_00]: They offered a job at $16 an hour with no benefits.

230
00:32:46,271 --> 00:32:53,918
[SPEAKER_00]: And of course, I think many of the provisions we have in this bill, thinking about labor peace, worker retention, are meant to solve that type of churn and prevent

231
00:32:54,238 --> 00:32:56,560
[SPEAKER_00]: that type of stuff from happening.

232
00:32:56,580 --> 00:32:59,863
[SPEAKER_00]: But I'll defer to my legal and policy team who can speak more to that.

233
00:33:01,485 --> 00:33:07,710
[SPEAKER_00]: The termination of longstanding service employees not only hurts the impacted workers and their families, but it hurts the city as well.

234
00:33:08,070 --> 00:33:11,113
[SPEAKER_00]: This is fundamentally an ordinance that's going to help the city of Medford.

235
00:33:12,314 --> 00:33:16,698
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, experienced employees are more familiar with the buildings they clean and the staff they support.

236
00:33:17,078 --> 00:33:24,744
[SPEAKER_00]: This translates into more reliable services and an extra set of eyes and ears to identify safety hazards, especially in a place like a public school.

237
00:33:25,244 --> 00:33:31,749
[SPEAKER_00]: That's why we believe the proposed ordinance should include the worker retention elements in the ordinance.

238
00:33:31,769 --> 00:33:36,093
[SPEAKER_00]: And we have similar elements in Cambridge and Boston ordinances as well.

239
00:33:37,022 --> 00:33:44,288
[SPEAKER_00]: Contract transitions not only cause disruptions for long-term employees, they can also cause disruptions for the services themselves and for the city.

240
00:33:44,608 --> 00:33:48,671
[SPEAKER_00]: That's why we would want something like a labor peace agreement, to help resolve some of that.

241
00:33:49,112 --> 00:33:53,135
[SPEAKER_00]: Labor peace is a common and legally well-established concept in public contracting.

242
00:33:53,515 --> 00:33:57,698
[SPEAKER_00]: It appears in laws and ordinances in many states and cities.

243
00:33:58,099 --> 00:34:02,202
[SPEAKER_00]: For example, here in Massachusetts, at Massport with Boston Logan Airport,

244
00:34:03,583 --> 00:34:09,467
[SPEAKER_00]: there are many contractors that have to comply with labor peace requirements for many years, and that's been done without issue.

245
00:34:10,047 --> 00:34:21,754
[SPEAKER_00]: The basic idea behind including a labor peace provision and the proposed ordinance is that the city's interest to ensure that there will be no labor disputes disrupting the services that are provided every day to residents of Medford.

246
00:34:22,314 --> 00:34:29,539
[SPEAKER_00]: Therefore, the proposal would require city contractors to negotiate labor peace agreements with labor unions who represent or seek to represent the workers.

247
00:34:31,953 --> 00:34:39,999
[SPEAKER_00]: It just requires that they take these certain steps to ensure that the services they provide to the city won't be disrupted and will maintain labor peace.

248
00:34:40,299 --> 00:34:41,380
[SPEAKER_00]: The name says it all, I think.

249
00:34:42,721 --> 00:34:52,528
[SPEAKER_00]: Finally, in order to protect area working standards that workers have fought to establish here in Medford, it's crucial that this ordinance provide a true living wage to the city-contracted workers.

250
00:34:53,068 --> 00:35:01,936
[SPEAKER_00]: The original version of the proposed ordinance would establish a fair wage and ensure a modest increase over the rate the janitors employed by Compass made prior to the termination.

251
00:35:02,636 --> 00:35:09,802
[SPEAKER_00]: In contrast, according to our calculations, the recent proposed revision would set a standard well below what these workers were making one year ago, right?

252
00:35:11,804 --> 00:35:12,885
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

253
00:35:13,545 --> 00:35:18,570
[SPEAKER_00]: And so we want to make sure that what this law does is that it doesn't undercut the area standards.

254
00:35:19,737 --> 00:35:35,345
[SPEAKER_00]: The prevailing wage law should require city contractors to pay their janitorial and security workers the higher of the wage and benefits rates established by the Federal Service Contract Act or the rate paid by the largest union that covers the relevant group of workers.

255
00:35:37,026 --> 00:35:48,672
[SPEAKER_00]: And with worker retention, it's about creating this 90-day transition period so that when a new contractor takes it over, there's this time where they can prove that they are the best qualified for the job.

256
00:35:49,625 --> 00:35:59,313
[SPEAKER_00]: This policy would ensure the government service contracts don't undercut market standards, the public receives high-quality services in exchange for their tax dollars, and the public funds support good jobs.

257
00:35:59,754 --> 00:36:04,658
[SPEAKER_00]: The policy would also prevent disruptions in city services due to worker turnover and labor unrest.

258
00:36:04,998 --> 00:36:17,929
[SPEAKER_00]: By adopting this time-tested and common-sense policy, the city council can take care of its hard-working service workers, safeguard taxpayer money, protect city services, and improve lives for both the workers and residents of Medford.

259
00:36:22,208 --> 00:36:22,648
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

260
00:36:22,668 --> 00:36:25,491
[SPEAKER_04]: Is there anyone else from your team who'd like to speak?

261
00:36:28,573 --> 00:36:43,545
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, I'd love to, if we could, you know, if Peter, if you could specifically speak to this ordinance and other communities or ordinances like this in other communities, I'd love to recognize you and good to see you.

262
00:36:47,128 --> 00:36:49,610
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you very much, Councilor Bears.

